al proliferation, stromal oedema, then tissue breakdown","Rising oestrogen with endometrial proliferation, tissue breakdown, then basement membrane changes","Increased vascularity, rising oestrogen with proliferation, then tissue breakdown","Stromal oedema, resolution of oedema, then rising oestrogen with proliferation","Rising oestrogen with proliferation, resolution of oedema, then increased vascularity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe menstrual cycle consists of three main phases with distinct endometrial changes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProliferative phase: \u003Cstrong\u003ERising oestrogen with endometrial proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as oestrogen levels increase, stimulating growth of the endometrial lining\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecretory phase: \u003Cstrong\u003EStromal oedema\u003C/strong\u003E develops under progesterone influence, along with secretory changes in endometrial glands\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMenstrual phase: \u003Cstrong\u003ETissue breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to withdrawal of hormonal support\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options present incorrect sequences. \u003Cstrong\u003EBasement membrane changes\u003C/strong\u003E are not a characteristic feature of any phase. While \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased vascularity\u003C/strong\u003E occurs throughout the cycle, it is not the defining feature of any particular phase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle is characterised by rising oestrogen levels causing endometrial growth.","Progesterone dominance in the secretory phase causes glandular development and stromal oedema.","Hormone withdrawal in the menstrual phase leads to tissue breakdown and shedding."],"references":["Reed BG, Carr BR. The Normal Menstrual Cycle and the Control of 